Once again it's Steph (the South African),what I would like to know from people in USA and anywhere else is why is the Vietnam war considered the 'most' traumatic and horrific ?<br>
I have watched many movies on experiences,Good morning Vietnam,Born on 4th July and many more and in all of them the common thread is the trauma of the war. My grandfather fought in the 2nd World War,he was 19 when he was recruited and was a fighter pilot just before his 20th birthday. When we spoke of the war,he had many horrific tales to tell me of. He had,had to shoot civilians and in one experience had flown so low that he saw the faces of the people running before he was given the command to drop the bomb. These sorts of experiences are traumatic and awful but why are they never spoken of. Is the trauma of the Vietnam war the knowledge that people back home were not rooting for you. And that your country made a huge mistake carrying on with the fight when it was already lost ? Is that maybe the worst trauma of the war,also being that when your soliders came home it was most definitely not to open arms. At least maybe when my grandfather spoke of his traumas and experiences in the 2nWW people listened and didn't shut him out.Anyway I just wanted to know first hand why ? So if you can enlighten me join my discussion. Thanx<br><br>
 
